 1931 or 1932, that at the last moment, this story, “Lips to Lips” (Usta k ustam), which finally had been accepted for publication, would not be printed after all. “Razbili nabor” (“They broke up the type”), my friend muttered gloomily. It was published only in 1956, by the Chekhov Publishing House, New York, in my collection Vesna v Fialte, by which time everybody who might have been suspected of remotely resembling the characters in the story was safely and heirlessly dead. Esquire